<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n40032f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n40" href="#n40032f">N40 (VI.B.28B)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n40all.htm#n40032f"> 32(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> naturism / animism ~</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">&ldquo;The feare of things invisible is the naturall seede of religion.&rdquo; This dictum of Thomas Hobbes, who enunciated it three hundred years ago, would be more acceptable, doubtless, if &ldquo;naturall&rdquo; came immediately before &ldquo;religion.&rdquo; But &ldquo;the feare of things invisible&rdquo; does most accurately describe the &ldquo;seede&rdquo; of the outcastes&apos; religion. From that &ldquo;feare&rdquo; it springs, and a rank crop it produces. It is called <i>naturism</i> when the fear is produced by natural phenomena, <i>animism</i> when &ldquo;spirits&rdquo; (<i>animae</i>)&mdash;so to call them for want of a better word&mdash;are what are feared. <small> Rev W.S. Hunt, <a name="WSHI1" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#WSHI1"><cite title="source">India's Outcastes: A New Era</cite></a> (1924) 43</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
